================================================================================
                    PROMPT ENGINEERING GUIDE FOR DEVELOPERS
================================================================================

Hey! Here's a breakdown of prompt engineering fundamentals. Think of this as
the "clean code" principles but for talking to LLMs.

================================================================================
PART 1: THE 8 CORE TIPS
================================================================================

TIP #1: USE XML TAGS
--------------------
Why: LLMs (especially Claude) were trained on XML-structured data. Tags help
     the model distinguish instructions from data.

How: Structure your prompt like this:

    <role>You are a backend developer.</role>
    <data>[paste your code or logs here]</data>
    <task>Find the bug causing the null pointer exception.</task>

Think of it like: Passing well-named parameters to a function instead of
                  one giant concatenated string.


TIP #2: BE SPECIFIC (THE "DIMWITTED INTERN" RULE)
-------------------------------------------------
Why: Vague words like "short" or "analyze" leave room for interpretation.
     The model will guess, and it often guesses wrong.

How: Quantify everything.

    BAD:  "Keep it short."
    GOOD: "Limit your response to exactly 3 bullet points."

    BAD:  "Analyze this code."
    GOOD: "List the top 5 performance bottlenecks in this code."

Think of it like: Writing a detailed Jira ticket vs. "fix the bug"


TIP #3: MIMIC THE DESIRED TONE
------------------------------
Why: LLMs are prediction engines. They complete the pattern you start.
     Sloppy input = sloppy output. Professional input = professional output.

How: Write your prompt in the same style you want the response.
     Want a formal technical doc? Write the prompt formally.
     Want casual Slack message? Write casually.


TIP #4: PROOFREAD YOUR PROMPTS
------------------------------
Why: Typos and grammar errors are "noise." They signal low-quality context,
     which pushes the model toward lower-quality output.

How: Treat prompts like production code. Review before sending.
     - Capitalize sentences
     - Fix typos
     - Use proper punctuation


TIP #5: WRITE IN YOUR STRONGEST LANGUAGE
----------------------------------------
Why: If you write in a language you're not fluent in, you'll use weird
     phrasing that confuses the model.

How: Write in your native language, even if you want output in English.
     The model translates better than you write awkward prompts.


TIP #6: PREFILLING (PRIME THE RESPONSE)
---------------------------------------
Why: This skips the "Sure! I'd be happy to help..." filler and forces
     the model into your desired format immediately.

How: End your prompt by starting the response yourself.

    Your prompt: "Convert this to JSON."
    Add at the end: "Here is the JSON: {"

    The model will continue from "{" directly into JSON format.

Think of it like: Stubbing out a function signature so the AI fills in the body.


TIP #7: AVOID NEGATIVE PROMPTING
--------------------------------
Why: "Don't think of a pink elephant" makes you think of it.
     LLMs struggle with negation the same way.

How: Tell the model what TO do, not what NOT to do.

    BAD:  "Don't write long sentences."
    GOOD: "Write short sentences under 15 words."

    BAD:  "Don't use technical jargon."
    GOOD: "Use simple language a non-developer would understand."


TIP #8: PUT INSTRUCTIONS IN USER MESSAGE (NOT SYSTEM)
-----------------------------------------------------
Why: The model pays more attention to User messages for execution details.
     System messages are better for high-level role setting.

How:
    System Prompt: "You are a senior Python developer." (simple)
    User Prompt:   [All your actual instructions, data, XML tags] (complex)


================================================================================
PART 2: THE MASTER TEMPLATE (R-C-T-F FRAMEWORK)
================================================================================

Copy-paste this structure for most prompts:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ROLE
Act as an expert [JOB TITLE, e.g., DevOps Engineer, Data Scientist].

# CONTEXT
I am working on [PROJECT/GOAL, e.g., debugging a production issue,
writing API documentation].

# TASK
[SPECIFIC INSTRUCTION, e.g., Review this code and identify memory leaks].

# CONSTRAINTS & FORMAT
- Tone: [Professional / Casual / Technical]
- Length: [e.g., under 200 words, 5 bullet points]
- Output Format: [e.g., JSON, Markdown table, numbered list]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------


================================================================================
PART 3: CODING-SPECIFIC TEMPLATE (S.P.E.C. FRAMEWORK)
================================================================================

When asking for code, always specify:

S - Stack:    Language, version, libraries (e.g., "Python 3.10 with Pandas")
P - Pattern:  Style guide (e.g., "PEP8", "OOP", "Functional")
E - Errors:   Edge cases and exception handling
C - Comments: Request docstrings/inline comments

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE
Python 3.10

# THE GOAL
I need a function that parses a CSV file and removes duplicate emails.

# REQUIREMENTS
1. Robustness: Handle edge cases (empty file, malformed rows). Include try/catch.
2. Style: Follow PEP8 conventions.
3. Documentation: Include docstrings explaining the logic.
4. Efficiency: Aim for O(n) time complexity.

# INPUT DATA
CSV with columns: name, email, signup_date

# OUTPUT
Provide the code in a single block, followed by a brief explanation
of how it handles errors.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------


================================================================================
PART 4: PROMPT TYPES & WHEN TO USE THEM
================================================================================

TYPE              | USE CASE                  | PRO TIP
------------------|---------------------------|----------------------------------
Open-ended        | Brainstorming, explain    | Add constraints to focus it
Specific/Closed   | Fact retrieval, lookup    | "Answer ONLY from provided text"
Multiple choice   | Classification            | "Return only the letter"
Hypothetical      | Scenario planning         | Ask AI to list assumptions first
Opinion-based     | Debate, perspectives      | Give a specific stance to argue

For code specifically:
- Code Completion:   Ask for error handling + docstrings
- Code Translation:  "Use idiomatic [target language] conventions"
- Code Optimization: "Explain Big O before and after"
- Code Debugging:    "Explain root cause, then fix, then prevention tip"


================================================================================
PART 5: DELIMITERS (SEPARATING SECTIONS)
================================================================================

Pick one style and be consistent:

1. Triple Quotes (great for text blocks)
   """
   Your text here
   """

2. XML Tags (most reliable for complex prompts)
   <input>data here</input>
   <instructions>task here</instructions>

3. Markdown Headers
   ### Context
   ### Task
   ### Format

4. Dashes (good for code blocks)
   ---
   code here
   ---


================================================================================
PART 6: QUICK REFERENCE CHEAT SHEET
================================================================================

BEFORE SENDING ANY PROMPT, CHECK:

[ ] Did I use tags/delimiters to separate sections?
[ ] Did I specify exact numbers (word count, bullet count)?
[ ] Did I define the output format (JSON, table, list)?
[ ] Did I write in the tone I want back?
[ ] Did I proofread for typos?
[ ] Did I say what TO do (not what NOT to do)?
[ ] Did I specify the audience?


================================================================================
PART 7: REAL EXAMPLE - BUG ANALYSIS PROMPT
================================================================================

BAD PROMPT:
"Look at this error and tell me what's wrong."

GOOD PROMPT:

<context>
I'm debugging a production issue in our Java Spring Boot application.
The audience for this analysis is the backend team.
</context>

<task>
Analyze the stack trace below. Identify:
1. The root cause of the exception
2. The exact line/method where it originates
3. Two potential fixes ranked by implementation effort
</task>

<stack_trace>
[paste your stack trace here]
</stack_trace>

<format>
- Use a numbered list for the 3 items above
- Keep each point under 50 words
- Include code snippets for the fixes
</format>


================================================================================
TL;DR - THE GOLDEN RULES
================================================================================

1. STRUCTURE   -> Use XML tags or delimiters
2. SPECIFICITY -> Quantify everything, no vague words
3. TONE        -> Write how you want the output to sound
4. POSITIVE    -> Say what to do, not what to avoid
5. ITERATE     -> First draft is rarely perfect, refine it

================================================================================
END OF GUIDE
================================================================================


================================================================================
              PROMPT TEMPLATES & EXAMPLES - A DEVELOPER'S HANDBOOK
================================================================================

This guide gives you ready-to-use templates you can copy-paste immediately.
Think of it as a "starter kit" for talking to LLMs effectively.

================================================================================
PART 1: UNDERSTANDING DELIMITERS (HOW TO SEPARATE SECTIONS)
================================================================================

Delimiters help the AI know where instructions end and data begins.
Pick one style and stay consistent.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
DELIMITER TYPE        | BEST FOR                  | EXAMPLE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Triple Quotes """     | Text blocks, articles     | """paste text here"""
XML Tags <tag>        | Complex, structured       | <input>data</input>
Markdown Headers ###  | Readable, organized       | ### Task
Colons and Labels     | Simple key-value          | INSTRUCTION: do this
Dashes ---            | Code blocks               | --- code here ---
Brackets [ ]          | Parameters, options       | [TONE]: Professional
BEGIN/END Markers     | Clear boundaries          | BEGIN TEXT ... END TEXT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXAMPLES OF EACH:

1. TRIPLE QUOTES
   ----------------
   Summarize the following article:

   """
   Climate change is affecting global temperatures. Scientists report 
   that 2024 was the hottest year on record.
   """

2. XML TAGS (Most reliable for complex prompts)
   ----------------
   You are a translator.

   <input_text>
   I love programming.
   </input_text>

   <target_language>
   Spanish
   </target_language>

   Translate the input text to the target language.

3. MARKDOWN HEADERS
   ----------------
   ### Role
   You are a helpful teacher.

   ### Task
   Explain this concept simply.

   ### Concept
   Photosynthesis

   ### Audience
   10-year-old student

4. COLONS AND LABELS
   ----------------
   INSTRUCTION: Fix the grammar errors.
   TEXT: She go to school yesterday and buyed a book.
   OUTPUT FORMAT: Corrected sentence only.

5. DASHES
   ----------------
   Review the code below for bugs.

   ---
   def add(a, b)
       return a + b
   ---

   List any errors found.

6. BRACKETS
   ----------------
   Write an email with these details:

   [TONE]: Professional
   [PURPOSE]: Meeting request
   [RECIPIENT]: Manager

7. BEGIN/END MARKERS
   ----------------
   Extract all names from this text:

   BEGIN TEXT
   John met Sarah at the coffee shop. Later, Michael joined them.
   END TEXT


WHY DELIMITERS MATTER:

   BAD (no delimiter):
   Translate hello world to French

   GOOD (with delimiter):
   Translate the following to French:
   """
   hello world
   """

The delimiter prevents confusion when your text contains words that
could be mistaken for instructions.


================================================================================
PART 2: THE 6 CORE PROMPTING TACTICS (STEP BY STEP)
================================================================================

TACTIC 1: SET CLEAR GOALS
-------------------------
What it means: Tell the AI EXACTLY what you want.

Formula: [Action] + [Format] + [Length] + [Audience]

BAD:  "Write something about APIs"
GOOD: "Write a 5-bullet summary of REST APIs for junior developers"

Examples:
  - "Write a 200-word explanation for a beginner."
  - "List the top 3 issues in bullet points."
  - "Generate a table comparing options A, B, and C."


TACTIC 2: GIVE CONTEXT
----------------------
What it means: Tell the AI the background and purpose.

Why: More context = better, more relevant answers.

BAD:  "Summarize this."
GOOD: "This is a customer complaint email. Summarize the main issue
       and the customer's desired resolution for our support team."

Template:
  "This is for [purpose/project]. The audience is [who].
   Based on this, [task]."


TACTIC 3: FEW-SHOT PROMPTING (SHOW EXAMPLES)
--------------------------------------------
What it means: Show 1-2 examples of what you want, then say "now do this."

Why: You're teaching by demonstration.

Example:
  Input: Cat -> Output: A small furry mammal with whiskers.
  Input: Dog -> Output: A domesticated canine known for loyalty.
  
  Now do the same for: Elephant.

Use this when:
  - You want a specific format
  - You want a specific tone
  - The AI keeps misunderstanding you


TACTIC 4: BE SPECIFIC
---------------------
What it means: Remove all vague words. Quantify everything.

BAD                              GOOD
--------------------------       ----------------------------------
"Keep it short"                  "Limit to 3 sentences"
"Analyze this"                   "List the top 5 issues"
"Make it better"                 "Improve readability and add comments"
"Write about climate"            "Write 200 words arguing for carbon tax"


TACTIC 5: ITERATE (TRY, FIX, TRY AGAIN)
---------------------------------------
What it means: The first answer is rarely perfect. Refine it.

Common follow-ups:
  - "Make it shorter."
  - "Use simpler words."
  - "Add a code example."
  - "Focus more on [specific part]."
  - "Remove the introduction, just give me the answer."

This is normal. Expect 2-3 rounds of refinement.


TACTIC 6: CHAIN-OF-THOUGHT (STEP-BY-STEP)
-----------------------------------------
What it means: Ask the AI to show its reasoning.

When to use: Math, logic, debugging, decisions, complex analysis.

Trigger phrases:
  - "Solve this step by step."
  - "Explain your reasoning."
  - "First list your assumptions, then give the answer."
  - "Walk me through your thought process."

Example:
  "To decide if we should use Strategy A or B, consider:
   (1) Performance impact
   (2) Implementation effort
   (3) Maintainability
   Then give a short conclusion with your recommendation."


================================================================================
PART 3: READY-TO-USE TEMPLATES (COPY-PASTE)
================================================================================

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 3.1: SUMMARIZE SOMETHING
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Summarize the following text as a [FORMAT] for a [AUDIENCE].
Length: about [X words / Y bullets].

Text:
"""
[paste text here]
"""

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
Summarize the following text as a bulleted list for a non-technical manager.
Length: about 5 bullets.

Text:
"""
[paste error log / requirements doc / article here]
"""

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 3.2: EXPLAIN IN SIMPLE TERMS
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Explain [CONCEPT] in simple terms for a [AUDIENCE].

Include:
1. A short 2-3 sentence overview.
2. A simple example.
3. One real-world analogy.

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
Explain REST APIs in simple terms for a new backend developer.

Include:
1. A short 2-3 sentence overview.
2. A simple example.
3. One real-world analogy.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 3.3: REWRITE / IMPROVE WRITING
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Rewrite the following text to be more [QUALITY: clear/formal/concise]
while keeping the same meaning.

Audience: [WHO WILL READ IT]

Text:
"""
[paste text here]
"""

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
Rewrite the following text to be more professional and concise
while keeping the same meaning.

Audience: my manager

Text:
"""
hey, i did that thing. let me know if it's ok or whatever
"""

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 3.4: GENERATE IDEAS
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Give me [NUMBER] ideas for [WHAT YOU NEED].

Constraints:
- Target audience: [WHO]
- Style/tone: [FUNNY, SERIOUS, PRACTICAL, ETC.]
- Other rules: [OPTIONAL]

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
Give me 10 ideas for YouTube videos about Java and Spring.

Constraints:
- Target audience: junior backend developers
- Style: practical and beginner-friendly


================================================================================
PART 4: CODING-SPECIFIC TEMPLATES
================================================================================

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 4.1: CODE HELPER (JAVA / SPRING BATCH EXAMPLE)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
You are an expert Java and Spring Batch developer.

Task: [DESCRIBE THE CODING TASK]

Context: [BRIEFLY EXPLAIN YOUR PROJECT, STAGES, CONSTRAINTS]

Requirements:
1. Use [FRAMEWORKS/PATTERNS].
2. Follow these rules: [E.G., GUARD CLAUSES, CONSISTENT LOGGING].
3. Output: [JAVA CODE ONLY / CODE + EXPLANATION / BULLET LIST].

Audience: An experienced Java developer.

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
You are an expert Java and Spring Batch developer.

Task: Refactor this processor to improve readability and validation.

Context: This is part of Stage 3 (left join on EMP_ID_NR) of an ETL-style
job. We're migrating logic from DataStage.

Requirements:
1. Centralize guard clauses for argument validation.
2. Use clear, predictable log messages.
3. Output Java code and then a brief bullet explanation of the main changes.

Audience: An experienced Java developer.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 4.2: EXPLAIN CODE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Explain what this code does, step by step, for a [JUNIOR/SENIOR] developer.
Then list 2-3 possible improvements.

Code:
```[LANGUAGE]
[YOUR CODE HERE]
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 4.3: DEBUG AN ERROR
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
I'm getting this error in [LANGUAGE/FRAMEWORK].

1. First, explain in simple words what the error usually means.
2. Then list possible causes in my case.
3. Then show me a fixed version of the code if possible.

Code:
```
[CODE HERE]
```

Error:
```
[ERROR MESSAGE HERE]
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 4.4: WRITE NEW CODE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Write [LANGUAGE] code that does the following:
[DESCRIBE THE TASK CLEARLY]

Requirements:
- Use [FRAMEWORK/LIBRARY] if needed.
- Follow [STYLE: E.G., CLEAN CODE, COMMENTS, SMALL METHODS].
- Add [UNIT TESTS / LOGGING / COMMENTS].

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
Write Java code that reads a CSV file, maps each row to an Employee object,
and logs invalid rows.

Requirements:
- Use Spring Batch.
- Follow clean code style with small methods.
- Add basic logging when a row is skipped.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 4.5: REFACTOR CODE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Refactor this [LANGUAGE] code to be more [READABLE / MAINTAINABLE / TESTABLE].
Keep the same behavior.
Then explain the main changes in a few bullets.

Code:
```
[YOUR CODE HERE]
```


================================================================================
PART 5: IMAGE PROMPT FORMULA
================================================================================

THE FORMULA:
[Subject] + [Action/Context] + [Art Style] + [Lighting/Color] + [Camera Angle]

TEMPLATE:
A [SUBJECT] [DOING WHAT] in [CONTEXT/PLACE], [ART STYLE OR MEDIUM],
[LIGHTING AND COLORS], [CAMERA ANGLE OR COMPOSITION].

EXAMPLES:
---------

1. A brave knight standing on a cliff overlooking a burning city,
   realistic digital painting, warm orange and red lighting,
   dramatic low-angle shot.

2. A cute cat wearing headphones and working on a laptop in a cozy room,
   anime illustration, soft warm lighting, close-up shot.

3. A futuristic city with flying cars during a rainstorm,
   cyberpunk digital art, neon blue and purple lighting,
   wide-angle aerial view.

4. A baby dragon learning to breathe fire with its mother in a cave,
   watercolor painting, soft golden light from the fire,
   mid-shot composition.

5. An astronaut planting a flag on an alien planet with purple plants,
   3D render style, high-contrast lighting,
   wide-angle lens from behind the astronaut.

BREAKDOWN:
----------
Subject      -> WHO or WHAT is in the image
Action       -> What are they DOING
Context      -> WHERE is this happening
Art Style    -> Digital art, watercolor, anime, 3D render, photo, etc.
Lighting     -> Warm, cold, neon, golden hour, dramatic, soft, etc.
Camera       -> Close-up, wide-angle, aerial, low-angle, portrait, etc.


================================================================================
PART 6: THE "DO EVERYTHING" UNIVERSAL TEMPLATE
================================================================================

When you're not sure what format to use, try this:

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
I want help with: [WHAT YOU'RE TRYING TO DO].

Context: [BRIEF BACKGROUND].

Please:
1. [FIRST THING YOU WANT]
2. [SECOND THING YOU WANT]
3. [THIRD THING YOU WANT]

Output format: [BULLETS, CODE ONLY, SHORT PARAGRAPH, ETC.]
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
I want help with: understanding this Java Spring Batch processor.

Context: This is part of an ETL job migrating from DataStage.

Please:
1. Explain what the code does in simple terms
2. Point out any obvious problems
3. Suggest a cleaner version of the code

Output format: bullets + revised Java code


================================================================================
PART 7: CLASSIFICATION / DECISION TEMPLATE
================================================================================

For tasks where you need the AI to make a choice or recommendation:

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
To decide [DECISION/QUESTION], consider:

(1) [CRITERION 1]
(2) [CRITERION 2]
(3) [CRITERION 3]

Then give a short conclusion with your recommendation.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
To decide whether we should use PostgreSQL or MongoDB for our new service,
consider:

(1) Query complexity - we need many JOIN operations
(2) Scalability requirements - expecting 10M records/month
(3) Team expertise - team knows SQL well, limited NoSQL experience

Then give a short conclusion with your recommendation.


================================================================================
PART 8: DOCUMENTATION / EXPLANATION TEMPLATE
================================================================================

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Explain the following code/concept in simple terms for [AUDIENCE].

Include:
1. A high-level summary (2-3 sentences).
2. A line-by-line walkthrough.
3. One example of how to use it in practice.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------


================================================================================
QUICK REFERENCE: WHICH TEMPLATE TO USE?
================================================================================

TASK                          | USE THIS TEMPLATE
------------------------------|----------------------------------
Summarize text                | Template 3.1
Explain a concept             | Template 3.2
Improve writing               | Template 3.3
Generate ideas                | Template 3.4
Explain code                  | Template 4.2
Fix a bug                     | Template 4.3
Write new code                | Template 4.4
Refactor code                 | Template 4.5
Generate an image             | Part 5 Formula
Make a decision               | Part 7
Not sure / complex task       | Part 6 Universal


================================================================================
TL;DR - THE GOLDEN RULES
================================================================================

1. USE DELIMITERS     -> Separate instructions from data (XML, """, ---)
2. BE SPECIFIC        -> Numbers, formats, audiences - no vague words
3. GIVE CONTEXT       -> Background + purpose = better answers
4. SHOW EXAMPLES      -> Few-shot prompting when format matters
5. ASK FOR STEPS      -> Chain-of-thought for complex reasoning
6. ITERATE            -> Refine in 2-3 rounds, that's normal

================================================================================
END OF HANDBOOK
================================================================================

================================================================================
         ADVANCED PROMPT ENGINEERING: KEYWORDS, FORMULAS & TECHNIQUES
                       A Developer's Complete Reference
================================================================================

This guide goes beyond basics. It covers the specific KEYWORDS that steer AI
responses, advanced formulas for accuracy, and coding-specific techniques.

Think of keywords as "steering wheels" - they tell the AI which direction to
go, how fast to drive, and what destination to reach.

================================================================================
PART 1: THE KEYWORD CATEGORIES
================================================================================

Keywords fall into 5 main categories. Master these, and you control the output.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 1: IDENTITY KEYWORDS (Who should the AI be?)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
These assign a "persona" to the AI. It switches from generic assistant to
specialist mode.

KEYWORD              | EXAMPLE
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
"Act as..."          | "Act as a senior software engineer"
"You are a..."       | "You are a strict code reviewer"
"Simulate..."        | "Simulate a job interview for a backend role"
"Pretend you are..." | "Pretend you are a database administrator"

WHY IT WORKS:
The AI has been trained on text from many perspectives. When you say
"Act as a senior engineer," you're telling it to weight its responses
toward that expertise level.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 2: ACTION KEYWORDS (What should the AI do?)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Vague verbs = vague results. Be specific about the ACTION.

INSTEAD OF "WRITE"   | USE THESE MORE SPECIFIC VERBS
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
                     | Draft, Outline, Brainstorm, Compose, Script

INSTEAD OF "LOOK AT" | USE THESE
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
                     | Analyze, Critique, Proofread, Summarize, Extract

INSTEAD OF "CHANGE"  | USE THESE
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
                     | Rephrase, Simplify, Translate, Expand, Condense

INSTEAD OF "FIX"     | USE THESE
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
                     | Debug, Refactor, Optimize, Patch, Correct

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 3: FORMAT KEYWORDS (What should the output look like?)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Without format instructions, the AI guesses (usually a wall of text).

KEYWORD              | WHEN TO USE
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
"Table"              | Comparing items, organizing data
"Bullet points"      | Lists, summaries, quick reads
"Step-by-step"       | Tutorials, processes, instructions
"Markdown"           | Headers, bold, structured documents
"CSV"                | Data for Excel/spreadsheets
"JSON"               | Structured data for code
"Code only"          | When you just want the code block
"Numbered list"      | Sequential items, rankings

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 4: TONE & AUDIENCE KEYWORDS (How should it sound?)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
These control the "voice" of the response.

KEYWORD              | EFFECT
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
"ELI5"               | Explain Like I'm 5 - ultra simple
"Professional"       | Formal, workplace appropriate
"Concise" / "Brief"  | Cuts out fluff, gets to the point
"Empathetic"         | Softer tone for difficult messages
"Technical"          | Uses jargon, assumes expertise
"For a [audience]"   | "For a beginner" / "For a CEO" / "For a child"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CATEGORY 5: CONSTRAINT KEYWORDS (What are the guardrails?)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
These STOP the AI from doing things you don't want.

KEYWORD              | EXAMPLE
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
"Only"               | "Give me the code only, no explanation"
"Limit to"           | "Limit to 3 sentences"
"Do not"             | "Do not use technical jargon"
"In the style of"    | "Write in the style of Shakespeare"
"Exclude"            | "Exclude any marketing language"
"Focus on"           | "Focus only on security issues"


================================================================================
PART 2: THE PERFECT PROMPT FORMULA
================================================================================

When stuck, fill in this formula:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Act as a [ROLE].
 Create a [TASK].
 Show it as [FORMAT].
 And ensure you [CONSTRAINT/TONE]."
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXAMPLES:

1. "Act as a fitness coach.
    Create a meal plan for next week.
    Show it as a table with days of the week.
    And ensure you include calorie counts for every meal."

2. "Act as a senior Java developer.
    Create a utility class for date formatting.
    Show it as clean, documented code.
    And ensure you follow Java naming conventions."

3. "Act as a tech writer.
    Create documentation for this API endpoint.
    Show it as Markdown with code examples.
    And ensure you write for junior developers."


================================================================================
PART 3: THE "HALLUCINATION-PROOF" FORMULA
================================================================================

LLMs can make things up (hallucinate). This formula minimizes that risk.

FORMULA:
[Context/Data] + [Task] + [Strict Constraint] + [Escape Hatch]

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
COMPONENT 1: THE CONTEXT (GROUNDING)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Instead of relying on AI's training data, PROVIDE the source material.

BAD:  "What is Company X's return policy?"
GOOD: "Context: [Paste the return policy text here]"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
COMPONENT 2: THE TASK
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
State exactly what you want done with that context.

"Task: Summarize the refund timeline."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
COMPONENT 3: THE STRICT CONSTRAINT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Lock the AI to ONLY your provided information.

"Answer using ONLY the information provided in the Context above.
 Do not use outside knowledge."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
COMPONENT 4: THE ESCAPE HATCH (CRUCIAL)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Give the AI permission to say "I don't know" instead of guessing.

"If the answer is not contained in the context, state
 'Information not available'. Do not guess."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Context:
"""
[Paste company policy / documentation / code here]
"""

Task: Extract all deadlines mentioned in this document.

Constraint: Use ONLY the information above. Do not add external knowledge.

Escape Hatch: If no deadlines are found, say "No deadlines found in document."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHY THE ESCAPE HATCH WORKS (Technical Explanation):
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LLMs are probabilistic engines. They predict the next likely token.

When you ask a vague question, the "probability cloud" of answers is huge,
and the model might pick something that sounds plausible but is wrong.

By adding "If you don't know, say so," you artificially boost the probability
of the "stop/unknown" token, making it easier for the model to choose
silence over creativity.


================================================================================
PART 4: CODING-SPECIFIC KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Code requires precision. These keywords are essential for programming tasks.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4.1 THE "STACK" KEYWORDS (Always specify these first)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
If you don't specify, the AI might give you Python 2 when you need Python 3,
or React class components when you want hooks.

KEYWORD              | EXAMPLE
---------------------|--------------------------------------------------
"In [Language]..."   | "In Python 3.11...", "In TypeScript..."
"Using [Framework]"  | "Using Spring Boot...", "Using React hooks..."
"Using [Library]"    | "Using Pandas...", "Using only standard library"
"Version [X]"        | "For Node.js version 18"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4.2 THE "ACTION" KEYWORDS FOR CODE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD    | WHAT IT DOES
-----------|--------------------------------------------------------------
Refactor   | Rewrite to be cleaner/efficient WITHOUT changing behavior
Debug      | Find and explain errors (always include error message!)
Optimize   | Improve performance (speed or memory)
Document   | Add comments, docstrings, JSDoc
Convert    | Translate from one language to another
Scaffold   | Generate the basic project structure
Annotate   | Add line-by-line explanations

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4.3 THE "QUALITY & ROBUSTNESS" KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
These move code from "it works" to "it's production-ready."

KEYWORD           | EFFECT
------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------
"Production-ready"| Includes error handling, logging, efficient logic
"Robust"          | Focuses on preventing crashes
"Secure"          | Prevents vulnerabilities (SQL injection, XSS, etc.)
"Sanitize"        | Clean/validate inputs before processing
"Scalable"        | Works with small AND large amounts of data
"Idiomatic"       | Uses the "correct" style for that language

EXAMPLES:
- "Write a production-ready Python script to upload files to S3."
- "Make this API call robust against network timeouts."
- "Write a SQL query but sanitize inputs to prevent injection."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4.4 THE "ARCHITECTURE & DESIGN" KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Use these for structural solutions.

KEYWORD           | EFFECT
------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------
"Design Pattern"  | Use established patterns (Singleton, Factory, Observer)
"Modular"         | Break into small, reusable functions
"RESTful"         | Follow REST API conventions
"SOLID"           | Follow SOLID principles
"DRY"             | Don't Repeat Yourself - eliminate duplication
"Clean Code"      | Follow clean code principles

EXAMPLES:
- "Implement a logger using the Singleton design pattern."
- "Refactor this to be modular so I can reuse the parsing logic."
- "Apply the DRY principle to this JavaScript function."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4.5 THE "MODERNIZATION" KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AI is trained on old AND new code. These force modern approaches.

KEYWORD             | EFFECT
--------------------|----------------------------------------------------------
"Modern"            | Latest syntax and approaches
"Deprecation-free"  | Avoid functions being removed in future versions
"ES6+" / "ES2020"   | Specific JavaScript version
"Functional"        | Immutability, pure functions, no side effects
"Object-Oriented"   | Classes, inheritance, encapsulation
"Async/Await"       | Modern async patterns (not callbacks)

EXAMPLES:
- "Rewrite this using modern ES6+ syntax."
- "Convert this callback-based code to async/await."
- "Use a functional programming approach with pure functions."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4.6 THE "TESTING" KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD      | MEANING
-------------|-------------------------------------------------------------
"Happy Path" | The scenario where everything goes right
"Edge Cases" | Weird scenarios (empty lists, nulls, negative numbers)
"Unit Test"  | Test individual functions in isolation
"Test Cases" | Generate multiple test scenarios
"TDD"        | Test Driven Development - write test BEFORE code
"Mock Data"  | Generate fake data for testing

EXAMPLES:
- "Write tests for the happy path first."
- "Now add tests covering edge cases."
- "Generate 5 unit test cases including division by zero."
- "Create mock employee data with 20 rows as CSV."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4.7 THE "PERFORMANCE" KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD              | EFFECT
---------------------|----------------------------------------------------------
"Time Complexity"    | Analyze or target specific Big O
"Big O"              | Same as above
"Memory Efficient"   | Minimize RAM usage
"Lazy Loading"       | Load resources only when needed
"Caching"            | Store results to avoid recomputation

EXAMPLE:
"Write a sorting algorithm. Ensure Time Complexity is better than O(n^2)."


================================================================================
PART 5: CODING PROMPT TEMPLATES (COPY-PASTE READY)
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 5.1: WRITE NEW CODE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Act as a Senior [LANGUAGE] Developer.

Write a [FUNCTION/CLASS/SCRIPT] that [DOES WHAT].

Requirements:
- Use [FRAMEWORK/LIBRARY] if needed.
- Handle [EDGE CASES: null inputs, empty lists, etc.].
- Follow [STYLE: clean code, PEP8, etc.].
- Include [COMMENTS/DOCSTRINGS/LOGGING].

Output: Code only, with comments.

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
Act as a Senior Java Developer.

Write a function that validates email addresses.

Requirements:
- Use regular expressions.
- Handle null inputs gracefully to avoid crashes.
- Follow Java naming conventions.
- Include Javadoc comments explaining the logic.

Output: Code only, with comments.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 5.2: DEBUG AN ERROR
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Analyze the following [LANGUAGE] code and the error message below.

1. Identify the root cause of the [ERROR TYPE].
2. Explain why this error occurs.
3. Propose a fix that [SPECIFIC SOLUTION].
4. Show the corrected code.

Code:
```[language]
[PASTE CODE HERE]
```

Error:
```
[PASTE ERROR MESSAGE HERE]
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 5.3: REFACTOR CODE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Refactor this [LANGUAGE] code to be more [GOAL: readable/maintainable/testable].

Requirements:
- Keep the same behavior (don't change what it does).
- Apply [PRINCIPLE: DRY, SOLID, Clean Code].
- Use [STYLE: modern syntax, design patterns].
- Add comments explaining major changes.

Code:
```[language]
[PASTE CODE HERE]
```

Output: Refactored code + bullet list of changes made.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 5.4: EXPLAIN COMPLEX CODE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Explain this [LANGUAGE] code step-by-step for a [AUDIENCE: junior/senior] developer.

Include:
1. A high-level summary (2-3 sentences).
2. A line-by-line walkthrough of the complex parts.
3. Any potential issues or improvements.

Code:
```[language]
[PASTE CODE HERE]
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 5.5: CODE REVIEW
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Act as a strict code reviewer.

Review this [LANGUAGE] code for:
1. Bugs or logic errors
2. Security vulnerabilities
3. Performance issues
4. Style/readability problems
5. Missing error handling

For each issue found, explain:
- What the problem is
- Why it matters
- How to fix it

Code:
```[language]
[PASTE CODE HERE]
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 5.6: GENERATE TESTS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Generate [NUMBER] unit tests for the following [LANGUAGE] function.

Include:
- Happy path tests (normal usage)
- Edge case tests (empty input, null, negative numbers)
- Error condition tests

Use [TESTING FRAMEWORK: JUnit, pytest, Jest, etc.].

Function to test:
```[language]
[PASTE CODE HERE]
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 5.7: THE QUICK SHORTCUT (Minimal prompt)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
When you need fast results with no fluff:

[LANGUAGE]. [TASK]. Code only.

EXAMPLES:
- "Python. Script to parse JSON and save to CSV. Code only."
- "Java. Method to check if string is palindrome. Code only."
- "SQL. Query to find duplicate emails. Code only."


================================================================================
PART 6: SPECIAL TRIGGER PHRASES
================================================================================

These phrases activate specific behaviors in the AI.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHRASE                          | EFFECT
--------------------------------|----------------------------------------------
"Let's think step by step"      | Forces reasoning for math/logic problems
"First, list your assumptions"  | Makes AI state what it's assuming
"Show your work"                | Explains the reasoning process
"Compare and contrast"          | Side-by-side analysis
"Pros and cons"                 | Balanced evaluation
"What are the tradeoffs?"       | Engineering decision analysis
"Walk me through"               | Detailed explanation
"Break this down"               | Decompose complex problems
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------


================================================================================
PART 7: KEYWORD QUICK REFERENCE TABLE
================================================================================

GOAL                    | KEYWORDS TO USE
------------------------|--------------------------------------------------
Set expertise level     | "Act as", "You are a", "Senior", "Expert"
Get specific format     | "Table", "Bullet points", "JSON", "Code only"
Control length          | "Limit to", "Concise", "In X words", "Brief"
Ensure quality code     | "Production-ready", "Robust", "Secure"
Force modern code       | "Modern", "ES6+", "Async/await", "Idiomatic"
Get clean structure     | "Modular", "Design pattern", "SOLID", "DRY"
Handle errors           | "Edge cases", "Error handling", "Validate"
Test code               | "Unit test", "Happy path", "Edge cases", "TDD"
Prevent hallucination   | "Only from context", "If unknown, say so"
Simple explanations     | "ELI5", "For a beginner", "In simple terms"
Skip the fluff          | "Code only", "No explanation", "Just the answer"


================================================================================
PART 8: GENERAL-PURPOSE TEMPLATES
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 8.1: UNIVERSAL PROMPT (Works for almost anything)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
You are a [ROLE: e.g., teacher, Java expert, designer].

Task:
[What do you want? One simple sentence.]

Context:
[Anything the AI should know: project, problem, background.]

Requirements:
- [Requirement 1]
- [Requirement 2]
- [Requirement 3]

Output format:
[bullets / short paragraph / code only / table / etc.]

Target audience:
[who will read this? e.g., beginner, manager, developer]

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 8.2: SUMMARIZATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Summarize the following text for a [AUDIENCE].

Goal:
[What you want: key points, action items, decisions, etc.]

Length and format:
[Number of bullets / ~X words / short paragraph.]

Text:
"""
[PASTE TEXT HERE]
"""

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 8.3: COMPARISON / DECISION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Compare [OPTION A] vs [OPTION B] for [USE CASE].

Consider:
1. [CRITERION 1]
2. [CRITERION 2]
3. [CRITERION 3]

Format: Table with pros/cons, then a recommendation.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEMPLATE 8.4: IMAGE GENERATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A [SUBJECT] [DOING WHAT] in [CONTEXT/PLACE],
[ART STYLE OR MEDIUM],
[LIGHTING AND COLORS],
[CAMERA ANGLE OR COMPOSITION].

EXAMPLE:
A futuristic robot playing chess in a neon-lit park,
synthwave digital art style,
pink and blue lighting,
wide-angle lens.


================================================================================
PART 9: COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID
================================================================================

MISTAKE                          | FIX
---------------------------------|---------------------------------------------
Vague verbs ("look at this")     | Use specific verbs (analyze, debug, refactor)
No format specified              | Always say: table, bullets, code only, etc.
No audience specified            | Add "for a junior dev" or "for a manager"
Assuming AI knows context        | Provide background explicitly
Not specifying language/version  | Always say "Python 3.11" or "Java 17"
Negative constraints only        | Say what TO do, not just what NOT to do
No escape hatch for unknowns     | Add "If unsure, say 'I don't know'"
One giant prompt                 | Break complex tasks into steps


================================================================================
TL;DR - THE GOLDEN RULES FOR DEVELOPERS
================================================================================

1. SPECIFY THE STACK    -> Language, version, framework FIRST
2. USE ACTION VERBS     -> Refactor, Debug, Optimize (not "fix" or "look at")
3. SET THE FORMAT       -> Code only, table, bullets, JSON
4. ADD CONSTRAINTS      -> Edge cases, error handling, no explanation
5. PROVIDE CONTEXT      -> Don't assume the AI knows your project
6. USE ESCAPE HATCHES   -> Let AI say "I don't know" vs. hallucinating
7. ITERATE              -> First answer rarely perfect, refine it

================================================================================
END OF GUIDE
================================================================================


================================================================================
          EXPERT PROMPT ENGINEERING: SENIOR DEVELOPER KEYWORDS
                    System Design, Security & Beyond
================================================================================

This guide covers ADVANCED keywords that distinguish a "coder" from a
"software engineer." These are essential for production systems, team
collaboration, and professional-grade code.

================================================================================
PART 1: POWER KEYWORDS - IDIOMATIC & SCAFFOLD
================================================================================

These two keywords are "force multipliers" - they save enormous time.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.1 THE "IDIOMATIC" KEYWORD
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHAT IT DOES:
Tells the AI: "Don't just translate logic into this language; use the specific
features that make this language unique." It forces "native speaker" code
instead of "tourist" code.

WITHOUT "IDIOMATIC" (Generic/C-style Python):
```python
numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
even_numbers = []
for i in range(len(numbers)):
    if numbers[i] % 2 == 0:
        even_numbers.append(numbers[i])
```
^ This works, but it looks like Java logic written in Python.

WITH "IDIOMATIC" (Pythonic):
Prompt: "Write Python to filter even numbers. Ensure code is idiomatic."

```python
numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
even_numbers = [num for num in numbers if num % 2 == 0]
```
^ Uses List Comprehension - faster and considered best practice in Python.

WHY IT MATTERS:
- Prevents code that gets rejected in code reviews
- Uses language-specific optimizations
- Makes code more readable to native developers

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.2 THE "SCAFFOLD" KEYWORD
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHAT IT DOES:
Builds the skeleton of a project (files, folders, imports) without writing
the inner logic. Gets you started instantly.

PROMPT EXAMPLE:
"Generate a project scaffold for a Node.js Express API. Include standard
folder structure and create placeholder files for routes and controllers.
Do not implement business logic yet."

OUTPUT:
```
/my-api
  /src
    /controllers
      userController.js
    /routes
      userRoutes.js
    app.js
  package.json
```

And stub code like this:
```javascript
// userController.js
exports.getAllUsers = (req, res) => {
  // TODO: Implement logic to fetch users from DB
  res.status(501).send("Not Implemented");
};

exports.createUser = (req, res) => {
  // TODO: Implement logic to create user
  res.status(501).send("Not Implemented");
};
```

WHY IT MATTERS:
- Saves 30+ minutes of boring setup time
- Ensures consistent project structure
- Gives you a clear starting point

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.3 THE "RATIONALE" KEYWORD (BONUS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Add this to understand WHY the AI made certain choices.

EXAMPLE:
"Refactor this function to be idiomatic. Explain your rationale."


================================================================================
PART 2: VISUAL & DIAGRAM KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Generate diagrams from text - incredibly useful for documentation.

KEYWORD        | OUTPUT TYPE                | EXAMPLE PROMPT
---------------|----------------------------|--------------------------------
"Mermaid"      | Flowcharts, sequence diags | "Create a Mermaid sequence diagram"
"Flowchart"    | Decision trees, processes  | "Visualize this if-else as flowchart"
"Graphviz/DOT" | Structural diagrams        | "Generate a Graphviz diagram"
"ASCII diagram"| Text-based visuals         | "Draw an ASCII diagram of this"

MERMAID EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Create a Mermaid sequence diagram showing authentication flow between
User, API, and Database."

OUTPUT:
```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    User->>API: Login Request
    API->>Database: Validate Credentials
    Database-->>API: User Data
    API-->>User: JWT Token
```

WHY MERMAID IS POWERFUL:
- Renders in GitHub, Notion, VS Code
- Version-controllable (it's just text)
- Easy to modify and share


================================================================================
PART 3: DEEP DEBUGGING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Go beyond "fix this bug" to understand HOW code executes.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "DRY RUN"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Asks AI to mentally execute code and show variable states at each step.

PROMPT:
"Dry run this loop with input [1, 5, 10]. Show state of variables
'i' and 'total' at each iteration."

OUTPUT:
```
Iteration 1: i=1, total=1
Iteration 2: i=5, total=6
Iteration 3: i=10, total=16
Final: total=16
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "TRACE"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Shows the execution PATH taken through code.

PROMPT:
"Trace the execution path if user input is null."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Instead of just fixing, explains WHY the bug happened.

PROMPT:
"The code fails with a timeout. Perform root cause analysis and suggest fixes."


================================================================================
PART 4: DEPENDENCY & LIBRARY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Control what tools the AI is allowed to use.

KEYWORD              | MEANING                              | EXAMPLE
---------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------------
"Standard Library"   | No external packages                 | "Using standard library only"
"Lightweight"        | Avoid heavy frameworks               | "Suggest lightweight solution"
"Vendor-agnostic"    | Works on AWS AND Azure               | "Make it vendor-agnostic"
"No dependencies"    | Pure language, nothing extra         | "Solve with no dependencies"
"Minimal imports"    | Use fewest libraries possible        | "Keep imports minimal"

EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Write a script to parse CSV files using standard library only (no Pandas)."


================================================================================
PART 5: STABILITY & OPERATIONS KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Essential for scripts and database operations in production.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "IDEMPOTENT" (CRITICAL FOR DEVOPS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MEANING: "Safe to run multiple times without changing result after first run."

WHY IT MATTERS:
If your install script runs twice, it shouldn't fail or duplicate things.

PROMPT:
"Write a bash script to install Docker. Make it idempotent so it doesn't
fail if Docker is already installed."

OUTPUT PATTERN:
```bash
#!/bin/bash
if ! command -v docker &> /dev/null; then
    echo "Installing Docker..."
    apt-get update && apt-get install -y docker.io
else
    echo "Docker already installed, skipping."
fi
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "ATOMIC"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MEANING: "All operations succeed, or none of them happen."

WHY IT MATTERS:
Critical for financial transactions - you can't debit one account without
crediting another.

PROMPT:
"Write a function to transfer money between accounts. Ensure the transaction
is atomic so we don't lose money if system crashes halfway."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "GRACEFUL DEGRADATION"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MEANING: "If main feature fails, fall back to something that still works."

PROMPT:
"Write a video player component. Implement graceful degradation so if
high-res fails, it plays low-res instead of showing an error."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SUMMARY TABLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD              | MEANING                    | USE CASE
---------------------|----------------------------|-------------------------
Idempotent           | Safe to run twice          | Scripts, installers
Atomic               | All or nothing             | Database transactions
Graceful Degradation | Fallback on failure        | User-facing features
Fault-tolerant       | Survives partial failures  | Distributed systems


================================================================================
PART 6: ALGORITHMIC APPROACH KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Dictate HOW the computer solves a problem.

KEYWORD        | MEANING                              | WHEN TO USE
---------------|--------------------------------------|---------------------------
"Recursive"    | Function calls itself                | Tree structures, math
"Iterative"    | Uses loops                           | Avoid stack overflow
"Greedy"       | Best choice at each step             | Optimization problems
"Brute Force"  | Try everything                       | When simplicity > speed
"Divide & Conquer" | Split problem into parts         | Sorting, searching
"Dynamic Programming" | Cache sub-problem results     | Optimization with overlap

EXAMPLE PROMPTS:

"Solve this tree traversal using an iterative approach to avoid stack overflow."

"Write a greedy algorithm to find minimum coins for change."

"First give me a brute force solution, then optimize it."


================================================================================
PART 7: ARCHITECTURE & DESIGN KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Force professional structural patterns.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "MICROSERVICES" vs "MONOLITHIC"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Specifies how system components connect.

PROMPT:
"Design a microservices architecture for a video streaming app."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "EVENT-DRIVEN"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
For async systems where things happen in response to events.

PROMPT:
"Write an event-driven Lambda function that triggers when file lands in S3."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "CLEAN ARCHITECTURE" / "HEXAGONAL"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Forces separation of concerns.

PROMPT:
"Refactor this API to follow Clean Architecture principles, separating
the 'Domain' from the 'Infrastructure' layer."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "12-FACTOR APP"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Gold standard methodology for SaaS applications.

PROMPT:
"Ensure this deployment config follows the 12-Factor App methodology."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "SOLID PRINCIPLES"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The 5 principles of object-oriented design.

PROMPT:
"Refactor this class to follow SOLID principles, especially Single
Responsibility and Dependency Inversion."


================================================================================
PART 8: SECURITY & SAFETY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Non-negotiable for production code.

KEYWORD           | WHAT IT PREVENTS              | EXAMPLE PROMPT
------------------|-------------------------------|-----------------------------
"OWASP Top 10"    | Standard web vulnerabilities  | "Check against OWASP Top 10"
"Zero Trust"      | Trusting internal requests    | "Use Zero Trust model"
"Sanitize"        | Injection attacks             | "Sanitize all user inputs"
"Least Privilege" | Over-permissioned code        | "Apply Least Privilege"
"Input Validation"| Malformed data                | "Add input validation"
"Escape"          | XSS attacks                   | "Escape output for HTML"

EXAMPLE PROMPTS:

"Review this login function for vulnerabilities, specifically checking
against the OWASP Top 10 (SQL Injection, XSS, etc.)."

"Generate an AWS IAM policy for this Lambda with Least Privilege principle."

"Sanitize all user inputs in this form before sending to database."


================================================================================
PART 9: PERFORMANCE & CONCURRENCY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For when code is slow or crashes under load.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "RACE CONDITION"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Bug where two things happen simultaneously and break the system.

PROMPT:
"Analyze this code for potential race conditions when two users save
at the exact same millisecond."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "LAZY LOADING"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Only load data when actually needed.

PROMPT:
"Implement lazy loading for images on this dashboard to improve startup."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "MEMOIZATION"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Cache expensive function results.

PROMPT:
"Optimize this recursive calculation using memoization."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "N+1 PROBLEM"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Classic database performance killer.

PROMPT:
"Check this ORM query for the N+1 problem and optimize using eager loading."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OTHER PERFORMANCE KEYWORDS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD              | MEANING
---------------------|------------------------------------------------------
"Connection Pooling" | Reuse database connections
"Async/Await"        | Non-blocking operations
"Caching"            | Store computed results
"Debounce/Throttle"  | Limit function call frequency
"Batch Processing"   | Handle data in chunks


================================================================================
PART 10: TESTING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Beyond "write a test" - specify HOW to test.

KEYWORD          | MEANING                              | EXAMPLE
-----------------|--------------------------------------|----------------------
"Happy Path"     | Everything goes right                | "Test the happy path"
"Edge Cases"     | Weird inputs (null, empty, negative) | "Cover edge cases"
"Regression Test"| Ensure old features still work       | "Write regression test"
"Smoke Test"     | Quick check if system starts         | "Create smoke test"
"Mock"           | Fake external systems                | "Mock the payment API"
"Stub"           | Simplified fake implementation       | "Stub the database"
"Integration Test"| Test components together            | "Write integration test"

EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Generate unit tests including happy path, edge cases (empty input, null,
negative numbers), and error conditions. Use pytest. Mock the database."


================================================================================
PART 11: META-PROMPTING (ADVANCED AI CONTROL)
================================================================================

Keywords that control HOW the AI thinks.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "TREE OF THOUGHTS"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AI explores multiple solutions before choosing best one.

PROMPT:
"Use a Tree of Thoughts approach to suggest 3 ways to solve this bug,
then tell me which is best and why."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "DO NOT HALLUCINATE"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Explicitly warns AI not to invent fake libraries or methods.

PROMPT:
"Write this import list. Do not hallucinate libraries; only use real,
installable packages."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "CHAIN OF VERIFICATION"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AI double-checks its own work.

PROMPT:
"Generate the SQL query, then perform chain of verification to ensure
it doesn't accidentally delete data."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "FEW-SHOT"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Provide examples for AI to follow.

PROMPT:
"I will provide a few-shot example of the format I want. Please follow it."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OTHER META KEYWORDS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"One-Liner"    -> Solve in single line of code
"Glossary"     -> Generate definitions of terms in code
"Annotate"     -> Add line-by-line explanations


================================================================================
PART 12: GIT & COLLABORATION KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For professional team workflows.

KEYWORD                | OUTPUT                    | EXAMPLE
-----------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------
"Conventional Commits" | Standardized messages     | "feat:", "fix:", "chore:"
"Changelog"            | Version history           | "Generate changelog entry"
"Conflict Resolution"  | Merge help                | "Suggest conflict resolution"
"PR Description"       | Pull request summary      | "Draft PR description"
"Code Review"          | Feedback on code          | "Review this as senior dev"

CONVENTIONAL COMMITS FORMAT:
```
feat: add user authentication
fix: resolve null pointer in login
chore: update dependencies
docs: add API documentation
refactor: simplify validation logic
```

EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Write a commit message for this change following Conventional Commits."


================================================================================
PART 13: API & INTEGRATION KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For connecting systems together.

KEYWORD        | MEANING                              | EXAMPLE
---------------|--------------------------------------|---------------------------
"Webhook"      | Event listener endpoint              | "Handle Stripe webhook"
"Payload"      | Data body being sent                 | "Construct JSON payload"
"Endpoint"     | API URL/route                        | "Create mock endpoint"
"Swagger/OpenAPI" | API documentation standard        | "Generate OpenAPI spec"
"REST" / "GraphQL" | API architecture style           | "Design RESTful endpoint"
"Rate Limiting"| Prevent API abuse                    | "Add rate limiting"

EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Generate an OpenAPI (Swagger) YAML definition for this Flask route."


================================================================================
PART 14: DATA ENGINEERING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For working with data pipelines and databases.

KEYWORD           | MEANING                           | EXAMPLE
------------------|-----------------------------------|---------------------------
"ETL"             | Extract, Transform, Load          | "Write ETL script"
"Upsert"          | Update if exists, else insert     | "Write upsert query"
"Pivot"           | Reshape data (rows to columns)    | "Pivot this dataset"
"Batch Processing"| Handle data in chunks             | "Use batch processing"
"Schema"          | Data structure definition         | "Generate JSON schema"
"Normalized"      | Proper database structure (no dup)| "Design normalized schema"
"Denormalized"    | Flattened for speed               | "Denormalize for reads"
"Seed"            | Reproducible random data          | "Generate with seed"

UPSERT EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Write a SQL query to upsert this user data to avoid duplicates."

ETL EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Write an ETL script to take data from CSV, clean the dates, and load
into PostgreSQL."


================================================================================
PART 15: FRONTEND & WEB KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For UI and browser compatibility.

KEYWORD          | MEANING                           | EXAMPLE
-----------------|-----------------------------------|---------------------------
"Responsive"     | Works on mobile and desktop       | "Make navbar responsive"
"Mobile-first"   | Design for phones first           | "Use mobile-first CSS"
"Pixel-perfect"  | Exact match to design             | "Convert to pixel-perfect"
"Dark Mode"      | Support light/dark themes         | "Add dark mode support"
"A11y"           | Accessibility (screen readers)    | "Add a11y best practices"
"Polyfill"       | Support old browsers              | "Include polyfill"
"Minified"       | Compressed for production         | "Give minified version"

ACCESSIBILITY PROMPT:
"Write this HTML button with a11y best practices (ARIA labels, keyboard nav)."


================================================================================
PART 16: MAINTENANCE & LEGACY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For dealing with existing code.

KEYWORD           | MEANING                          | EXAMPLE
------------------|----------------------------------|---------------------------
"Technical Debt"  | Quick fixes that hurt later      | "Highlight technical debt"
"Hardening"       | Secure before deployment         | "Steps for hardening"
"Legacy"          | Old, hard-to-change code         | "Explain this legacy code"
"Migration"       | Moving to new system             | "Plan database migration"
"Deprecation"     | Features being removed           | "Check for deprecations"

EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Analyze this code and highlight areas of potential technical debt."


================================================================================
PART 17: COMPLETE KEYWORD REFERENCE TABLE
================================================================================

CATEGORY         | TOP KEYWORDS
-----------------|----------------------------------------------------------
Structure        | Scaffold, Modular, Clean Architecture, SOLID
Quality          | Idiomatic, Production-ready, Robust, Type-safe
Safety           | Idempotent, Atomic, Sanitize, Least Privilege
Performance      | Lazy Loading, Memoization, N+1, Batch Processing
Testing          | Happy Path, Edge Cases, Mock, Regression
Security         | OWASP, Zero Trust, Input Validation, Escape
Debugging        | Dry Run, Trace, Root Cause Analysis
Visualization    | Mermaid, Flowchart, ASCII Diagram
Data             | ETL, Upsert, Schema, Normalized, Pivot
API              | Webhook, Payload, Swagger, Rate Limiting
Git              | Conventional Commits, Changelog, PR Description
Meta             | Tree of Thoughts, Chain of Verification, Few-Shot


================================================================================
PART 18: SENIOR ENGINEER PROMPT TEMPLATE
================================================================================

Combine keywords from multiple categories for powerful prompts:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Act as a [SENIOR ROLE].

[TASK VERB] a [COMPONENT] that [DOES WHAT].

Architecture:
- Follow [PATTERN: Clean Architecture / Microservices / Event-driven]
- Apply [PRINCIPLES: SOLID / DRY / 12-Factor]

Quality Requirements:
- Make it [QUALITY: production-ready / robust / idempotent]
- Use [STYLE: idiomatic / modern] [LANGUAGE] syntax
- Handle [SAFETY: edge cases / race conditions / null inputs]

Security:
- Apply [SECURITY: Least Privilege / input validation / sanitization]
- Check against [STANDARD: OWASP Top 10]

Output:
- Include [DOCS: comments / docstrings / Mermaid diagram]
- Add [TESTS: unit tests / happy path / edge cases]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

FILLED EXAMPLE:
---------------
Act as a Senior Backend Engineer.

Design an API endpoint that handles user registration.

Architecture:
- Follow Clean Architecture with separate domain and infrastructure layers
- Apply SOLID principles

Quality Requirements:
- Make it production-ready with proper error handling and logging
- Use idiomatic Python with type hints
- Handle edge cases (duplicate emails, invalid input, rate limiting)

Security:
- Apply input validation and sanitization
- Check against OWASP Top 10 (especially injection attacks)

Output:
- Include docstrings and inline comments
- Add unit tests for happy path and edge cases
- Generate a Mermaid sequence diagram of the registration flow


================================================================================
TL;DR - THE EXPERT ENGINEER'S CHECKLIST
================================================================================

Before sending any production-level prompt, consider:

[ ] STRUCTURE    -> Scaffold, Clean Architecture, Modular
[ ] QUALITY      -> Idiomatic, Production-ready, Type-safe
[ ] SAFETY       -> Idempotent, Atomic, Edge cases
[ ] SECURITY     -> Sanitize, Least Privilege, OWASP
[ ] PERFORMANCE  -> Lazy loading, Caching, N+1 check
[ ] TESTING      -> Happy path, Edge cases, Mocks
[ ] DOCS         -> Comments, Mermaid diagrams, Changelog

================================================================================
END OF EXPERT GUIDE
================================================================================










================================================================================
     COMPLETE PROMPT ENGINEERING REFERENCE: SPECIALIST KEYWORDS,
              CHAIN-OF-THOUGHT, AND THE ULTIMATE CHEAT SHEET
================================================================================

This is the FINAL guide covering specialist domains (Cloud, AI/ML, SRE),
Chain-of-Thought prompting techniques, and a complete cheat sheet organized
by development phase.

================================================================================
PART 1: CLOUD & INFRASTRUCTURE KEYWORDS (IaC)
================================================================================

For code that manages servers (Terraform, CloudFormation, AWS CDK).

KEYWORD           | MEANING                              | EXAMPLE PROMPT
------------------|--------------------------------------|---------------------------
"Provision"       | Create cloud resources               | "Provision an AWS Lambda"
"Drift"           | Real setup doesn't match code        | "Detect drift in stack"
"Cold Start"      | Serverless function wake-up delay    | "Minimize cold start latency"
"Region-agnostic" | Works in any AWS/Azure region        | "Make policy region-agnostic"
"Infrastructure as Code" | Define infra in files        | "Write IaC for this setup"
"Teardown"        | Delete/destroy resources             | "Add teardown script"
"State file"      | Terraform's record of what exists    | "Handle state file locking"

EXAMPLE PROMPTS:

"Write a Terraform script to provision an AWS Lambda function and S3 bucket."

"Optimize this Lambda function to minimize cold start latency."

"Explain how to detect drift in this CloudFormation stack."


================================================================================
PART 2: AI ENGINEERING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For coding WITH AI models (not just using them).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "RAG" (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The technique of feeding a model your own data/documents.

PROMPT:
"Write a Python script to implement a basic RAG pipeline using LangChain."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "EMBEDDINGS"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Mathematical vector representations of text.

PROMPT:
"Write code to convert these user comments into vector embeddings."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "INFERENCE"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The act of the model actually running/thinking.

PROMPT:
"Optimize this model code for faster inference on a CPU."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "TOKEN LIMIT"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Maximum input/output size for a model.

PROMPT:
"Write a function to truncate text so it fits within the 8k token limit."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OTHER AI KEYWORDS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | MEANING
------------------|------------------------------------------------------
"Fine-tuning"     | Training model on custom data
"Prompt injection"| Security attack via malicious prompts
"Hallucination"   | Model making things up
"Context window"  | How much text model can "see"
"Temperature"     | Randomness/creativity setting
"Few-shot"        | Teaching by examples in the prompt
"Zero-shot"       | No examples, just instructions


================================================================================
PART 3: CODE METRICS KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Measure code quality with mathematical formulas.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "CYCLOMATIC COMPLEXITY"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A score of how many "paths" (if/else statements) are in code. Lower = better.

PROMPT:
"Refactor this function to reduce its Cyclomatic Complexity below 10."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "COGNITIVE COMPLEXITY"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A score of how hard the code is for a HUMAN to understand.

PROMPT:
"This code is hard to read. Refactor it to lower the Cognitive Complexity."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "CODE SMELL"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Patterns that aren't bugs but indicate "bad design."

Common Code Smells:
- Long Method (function too big)
- God Class (class does everything)
- Feature Envy (method uses another class's data too much)
- Duplicate Code
- Dead Code

PROMPT:
"Review this class for code smells like Long Method or God Class."


================================================================================
PART 4: EVENT HANDLING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Essential for UI and high-traffic APIs.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "DEBOUNCE"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MEANING: "Wait for user to STOP doing something before acting."

USE CASE: Search bars - don't fire API call for every keystroke.

PROMPT:
"Implement debounce on the search bar so it waits 300ms after typing stops."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "THROTTLE"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MEANING: "Only allow this action once every X seconds."

USE CASE: Prevent users clicking "Buy" button multiple times.

PROMPT:
"Write a throttle function to limit button clicks to once per second."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "EXPONENTIAL BACKOFF"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MEANING: "If server fails, wait 1s, then 2s, then 4s, then 8s..."

USE CASE: Retrying failed API requests without overwhelming server.

PROMPT:
"Implement exponential backoff strategy for retrying failed API requests."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
COMPARISON:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD    | BEHAVIOR                    | USE CASE
-----------|-----------------------------|---------------------------------
Debounce   | Wait until activity stops   | Search input, resize events
Throttle   | Limit frequency             | Scroll events, button clicks
Backoff    | Increasing wait on failure  | API retries, reconnection


================================================================================
PART 5: DATABASE INTERNALS KEYWORDS
================================================================================

KEYWORD           | MEANING                              | EXAMPLE PROMPT
------------------|--------------------------------------|---------------------------
"Indexing"        | Speed up queries                     | "Suggest indexing strategies"
"Sharding"        | Split DB across servers              | "Implement sharding by UserID"
"ACID Compliance" | Data validity guarantee              | "Check ACID compliance"
"Deadlock"        | Two queries waiting for each other   | "Detect potential deadlocks"
"Connection Pool" | Reuse DB connections                 | "Add connection pooling"
"Query Plan"      | How DB executes a query              | "Analyze the query plan"
"Denormalization" | Flatten for read speed               | "Denormalize for faster reads"

ACID EXPLAINED:
- Atomicity: All or nothing
- Consistency: Data stays valid
- Isolation: Transactions don't interfere
- Durability: Saved data survives crashes


================================================================================
PART 6: SRE & RELIABILITY KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For systems that CANNOT fail (banking, healthcare, production systems).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "INSTRUMENT"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Add code that measures HOW the code is running (logs, metrics).

PROMPT:
"Instrument this API endpoint to log execution time of every database query."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "CIRCUIT BREAKER"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Pattern that stops calling a broken service repeatedly.

States: CLOSED (normal)  OPEN (failing, stop trying)  HALF-OPEN (test again)

PROMPT:
"Implement the Circuit Breaker pattern for the payment gateway connection."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "FUZZING"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Testing by throwing random garbage data at code to see if it crashes.

PROMPT:
"Write a Python script to perform fuzzing on my input parser."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "TELEMETRY"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The logs/metrics/traces your app sends out for monitoring.

PROMPT:
"Design a telemetry structure for tracking user clicks and errors."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OTHER SRE KEYWORDS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | MEANING
------------------|------------------------------------------------------
"SLO/SLA/SLI"     | Service Level Objective/Agreement/Indicator
"Runbook"         | Step-by-step guide for handling incidents
"Postmortem"      | Analysis after an incident
"Canary deploy"   | Release to small % of users first
"Blue-green"      | Two identical environments, switch between them
"Rolling update"  | Update servers one at a time


================================================================================
PART 7: CONCURRENCY & THREADING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

For high-performance code doing multiple things at once.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "MUTEX" (Mutual Exclusion)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A lock that stops two threads from writing to same variable simultaneously.

PROMPT:
"Protect this shared counter variable using a Mutex."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "DEADLOCK"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Two processes waiting for each other forever.

PROMPT:
"Analyze this multi-threaded code for potential deadlock scenarios."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD: "NON-BLOCKING"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Code doesn't freeze the UI/screen while waiting for data.

PROMPT:
"Rewrite this file upload function to be non-blocking using async/await."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OTHER CONCURRENCY KEYWORDS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | MEANING
------------------|------------------------------------------------------
"Thread-safe"     | Safe to use from multiple threads
"Semaphore"       | Like mutex but allows N threads
"Race condition"  | Bug when timing causes unexpected results
"Volatile"        | Variable that can change unexpectedly
"Lock-free"       | Concurrent without traditional locks
"Atomic operation"| Cannot be interrupted mid-execution


================================================================================
PART 8: CRYPTOGRAPHY & AUTH KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Security requires precise vocabulary. Wrong word = insecure code.

KEYWORD           | MEANING                              | EXAMPLE PROMPT
------------------|--------------------------------------|---------------------------
"Salt"            | Random data added before hashing     | "Add unique salt per user"
"Hash"            | One-way transformation               | "Hash passwords with bcrypt"
"JWT"             | JSON Web Token for auth              | "Validate JWT in header"
"Symmetric"       | Same key encrypts/decrypts           | "Use AES symmetric encryption"
"Asymmetric"      | Public/private key pair              | "Use RSA asymmetric encryption"
"HMAC"            | Hash-based message authentication    | "Sign payload with HMAC"
"OAuth"           | Authorization framework              | "Implement OAuth 2.0 flow"
"CORS"            | Cross-Origin Resource Sharing        | "Configure CORS headers"

EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Write a function to hash passwords. Ensure you add a unique salt for
every user and use bcrypt with cost factor 12."


================================================================================
PART 9: SPECIFIC REFACTORING KEYWORDS
================================================================================

"Refactor" is general. These are specific MOVES you can request.

KEYWORD           | WHAT IT DOES                         | EXAMPLE
------------------|--------------------------------------|---------------------------
"Extract Method"  | Move chunk to new helper function    | "Apply Extract Method"
"Inline"          | Put small function back into caller  | "Inline this helper"
"De-couple"       | Break dependency between components  | "De-couple email from signup"
"Extract Class"   | Move related methods to new class    | "Extract validation class"
"Rename"          | Change names for clarity             | "Rename for clarity"
"Move Method"     | Relocate method to better class      | "Move to where data lives"
"Replace conditional" | Replace if/else with polymorphism | "Use strategy pattern"

EXAMPLE PROMPT:
"Review this long function and apply Extract Method to the validation logic
and the database saving logic."


================================================================================
PART 10: DATA STRUCTURE KEYWORDS
================================================================================

Tell AI exactly which structure to use for optimal performance.

STRUCTURE         | USE CASE                   | TIME COMPLEXITY (LOOKUP)
------------------|----------------------------|-------------------------
"HashMap/Dict"    | Fast key-value lookup      | O(1)
"Array/List"      | Ordered sequence           | O(n) search, O(1) index
"Set"             | Unique items, fast lookup  | O(1)
"Queue (FIFO)"    | First-in-first-out         | O(1) enqueue/dequeue
"Stack (LIFO)"    | Last-in-first-out          | O(1) push/pop
"Tree"            | Hierarchical data          | O(log n) balanced
"Graph"           | Networks, relationships    | Varies
"Heap"            | Priority queue             | O(log n) insert/extract

EXAMPLE PROMPTS:

"Optimize this search function by converting the list into a HashMap."

"Model the user relationships as a Graph."

"Process these orders using a Queue (First-In-First-Out) approach."


================================================================================
PART 11: CHAIN-OF-THOUGHT (CoT) PROMPTING
================================================================================

Chain-of-Thought is a technique that forces the AI to "show its work"
instead of jumping to an answer. Essential for math, logic, and debugging.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11.1 THE "GOLDEN" TRIGGER PHRASE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The single most effective phrase to activate CoT reasoning:

>>> "Let's think step by step."

This one phrase can dramatically improve accuracy on complex problems.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11.2 CORE CoT KEYWORDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Use 1-2 of these per prompt (not all at once):

REASONING TRIGGERS:
- "think step by step"
- "show your reasoning"
- "explain your thinking"
- "break the problem down"
- "reason it out in stages"
- "walk through this slowly"
- "explain each step clearly"
- "describe your thought process"

PLANNING TRIGGERS:
- "outline your plan before answering"
- "first analyze, then answer"
- "list the steps needed"
- "identify the subproblems"
- "start with a high-level plan, then details"

VERIFICATION TRIGGERS:
- "check your work"
- "verify each step"
- "double-check your reasoning"
- "look for edge cases"
- "explain why this solution is correct"

STRUCTURE TRIGGERS:
- "first... then... finally..."
- "use numbered steps"
- "separate analysis and final answer"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11.3 THE CoT TEMPLATE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[CONTEXT/ROLE]
Act as a [Role, e.g., Senior Developer / Mathematician].

[THE TASK]
Here is the problem: [Insert your complex problem here]

[THE TRIGGER - KEYWORDS]
Please solve this by following these rules:
1. Let's think step by step.
2. Break it down into clear components.
3. Show your work for every step.
4. Therefore, provide the final answer only after the reasoning trace.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11.4 CoT EXAMPLES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXAMPLE 1: MATH PROBLEM

Without CoT:
"If a store offers 25% off $80, then 10% off the sale price, what's final?"

With CoT:
"If a store offers 25% off $80, then 10% off the sale price, what's final?
Think step by step and show your calculations."

AI Output:
Step 1: Calculate 25% off $80  $80  0.25 = $20 discount  $60
Step 2: Calculate 10% off $60  $60  0.10 = $6 discount  $54
Final price: $54

---

EXAMPLE 2: LOGIC PUZZLE

Without CoT:
"Tom is taller than Jane. Jane is taller than Mike. Is Tom taller than Mike?"

With CoT:
"Tom is taller than Jane. Jane is taller than Mike. Is Tom taller than Mike?
Reason through this carefully before answering."

AI Output:
Tom > Jane (given)
Jane > Mike (given)
Therefore: Tom > Jane > Mike
Yes, Tom is taller than Mike.

---

EXAMPLE 3: DEBUGGING CODE

Without CoT:
"Why isn't this code working? for i in range(5): print(i + 1"

With CoT:
"Why isn't this code working? Break it down piece by piece and identify
the issue. for i in range(5): print(i + 1"

AI Output:
Step 1: Check syntax  missing closing parenthesis on print()
Step 2: Should be print(i + 1)
Fix: Add the missing ) at the end.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11.5 CoT FOR JAVA/CODING SPECIFICALLY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

GENERATION KEYWORDS:
- "think step by step before writing code"
- "first outline the approach, then write the code"
- "explain your reasoning before showing the code"
- "identify edge cases before coding"

DEBUGGING KEYWORDS:
- "analyze this code for bugs"
- "walk through the code step by step"
- "identify possible root causes"
- "propose specific fixes"
- "show the corrected code"

REFACTORING KEYWORDS:
- "keep the behavior exactly the same"
- "improve readability"
- "extract helper methods"
- "make it production-ready"

JAVA CoT TEMPLATE:
-----------------
Act as a senior Java developer.

Here is my code:
```java
[PASTE CODE HERE]
```

Please:
1. Think step by step before making changes.
2. Identify edge cases and potential bugs.
3. Explain your reasoning.
4. Show the improved code.
5. Verify the changes maintain the same behavior.


================================================================================
PART 12: THE ULTIMATE CHEAT SHEET (BY DEVELOPMENT PHASE)
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 1: SETUP & PLANNING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | WHAT IT DOES                    | EXAMPLE
------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------
"Act as..."       | Sets the persona/expertise     | "Act as a Senior Architect"
"Scaffold"        | Creates files/folders          | "Create project scaffold"
"Skeleton"        | Basic code structure           | "Write class skeleton"
"Design Pattern"  | Forces standard structures     | "Use Factory pattern"
"Microservices"   | Distributed architecture       | "Design microservices"
"Event-Driven"    | Async triggers                 | "Make it event-driven"
"Mock"            | Fake data for planning         | "Generate mock user data"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 2: CODING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | WHAT IT DOES                    | EXAMPLE
------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------
"Idiomatic"       | Uses native language features  | "Make it Pythonic"
"Modular"         | Small, reusable pieces         | "Keep functions modular"
"Standard Library"| No external packages           | "Standard library only"
"Functional"      | Pure functions/immutability    | "Use functional style"
"Type-safe"       | Prevents type errors           | "Type-safe TypeScript"
"Modern"          | Latest syntax                  | "Use modern ES6+ syntax"
"Boilerplate"     | Setup/template code            | "Write the boilerplate"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 3: DATA & LOGIC
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | WHAT IT DOES                    | EXAMPLE
------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------
"Upsert"          | Update if exists, else insert  | "Write upsert query"
"Idempotent"      | Safe to run multiple times     | "Make script idempotent"
"Atomic"          | All-or-nothing transactions    | "Ensure atomic transfer"
"Recursive"       | Function calls itself          | "Write recursive search"
"Memoization"     | Cache results for speed        | "Optimize with memoization"
"ETL"             | Extract, Transform, Load       | "Write ETL script"
"Regex"           | Pattern matching               | "Write regex for emails"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 4: SECURITY & QUALITY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | WHAT IT DOES                    | EXAMPLE
------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------
"Sanitize"        | Clean inputs to stop hacks     | "Sanitize all inputs"
"OWASP Top 10"    | Check common vulnerabilities   | "Review for OWASP Top 10"
"Edge Cases"      | Handle weird scenarios         | "Handle edge cases"
"Production-ready"| Add logging/error handling     | "Make production-ready"
"Robust"          | Doesn't crash easily           | "Make error handling robust"
"Circuit Breaker" | Stop calling broken services   | "Implement circuit breaker"
"Complexity"      | Measure code difficulty        | "Reduce cyclomatic complexity"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PHASE 5: DEBUGGING & EXPLANATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEYWORD           | WHAT IT DOES                    | EXAMPLE
------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------------
"Root Cause"      | Find WHY it broke              | "Perform root cause analysis"
"Dry Run"         | Step through code mentally     | "Dry run with input X"
"ELI5"            | Explain simply                 | "Explain ELI5"
"Annotate"        | Add explanatory comments       | "Annotate every line"
"Visualize"       | Draw diagrams                  | "Visualize as Mermaid chart"
"Refactor"        | Rewrite without changing output| "Refactor to be cleaner"
"Step by step"    | Chain-of-thought reasoning     | "Think step by step"


================================================================================
PART 13: THE MASTER FORMULA
================================================================================

Combine ONE keyword from each layer for powerful prompts:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Act as a [ROLE].
 Write a [TASK] that is [QUALITY KEYWORD].
 Ensure it handles [DATA KEYWORD] and uses [SECURITY KEYWORD].
 Output as [FORMAT]."
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXAMPLE 1 (DevOps):
"Act as a Senior DevOps Engineer.
 Write a Python script to backup a database.
 Ensure it is idempotent and uses atomic transactions.
 Sanitize the inputs.
 Output code only."

EXAMPLE 2 (Backend):
"Act as a Senior Java Developer.
 Write a REST endpoint for user registration.
 Ensure it is production-ready and handles edge cases.
 Sanitize all inputs and check OWASP Top 10.
 Output code with comments."

EXAMPLE 3 (Data):
"Act as a Data Engineer.
 Write an ETL script for CSV to PostgreSQL.
 Ensure it uses batch processing and is idempotent.
 Add logging for debugging.
 Output code with explanation."


